title: Choosing the right statistical test
description: How to choose a statistical test for different types of clinical trial data
contents:
Contents
Motivation to write
TL;DR

Motivation to write
Using the right statistical test - and using it in the right way - is critical for clinical trials. The choice of a test depends on many factors (i.e hypothesis, study design, sample size etc) but the focus on the blog post is on selecting a statistical test.
The blog will be a reference for my work but I hope it will be useful for anyone else who is involved in clinical research.
The main reference materials come from the Handbook of Biological Statistics by John H. McDonald and Statistics at Square One

title: {.tabset} in distill?
description: When tabset fails, do this to create tab panels in distill articles
contents:
Contents
Why .tabset and why it fails?
Workaround
End results


Why .tabset and why it fails?
Interactive articles are more powerful to convey information to readers. Better visualisation helps readers to digest the content faster.
It is easy to include tabs in html article. The .tabset function can be included at a heading (say level 2) and all the following subheading (i.e. level 3) will be arranged in tabbed panels. However, this approach does not work with distill. This is confirmed in a 2018 post here but the authors did mention they wish to use jqueryUI tabsets in the future.
Note: This information is accurate as of 17th January 2022
Workaround
Garrik Aden-Buie suggested the panelset function from xaringanExtra to circumvent this issue, but the approach requires the fenced-div syntax as followed:


show code

xaringanExtra::use_panelset()

# ::::: {.panelset}
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# # Tab One {.panel-name}
#
# Content for tab one here
# 
# ### Sub heading one
#
# **Psst: see tab two!** 
#
# :::
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# ## Tab Two {.panel-name}
#
# This is how I feel when I try to code
#
# ![](https://media.giphy.com/media/EJsTKyvaYzvm8/giphy.gif)
#
# :::
#
# ::: {.panel}
#
# ## Tab Three {.panel-name}
#
# Content for tab three here
#
# :::
#
# :::::



End results
The end results look like this:

Tab One
Content for tab one here
Sub heading one
Psst: see tab two!
Tab Two
This is how I feel when I try to code

Tab Three
Content for tab three here

title: Simulating Survival Data
description: A short description on simulating survival-type data using the `sim.survdata` function
contents:
Contents
TL;DR

The main reference materials (1 and 2) come from Jeffrey Harden and Jonathan Kropko.
TL;DR
The sim.survdata function simulates survival data (the duration) without specifying a specific distribution for the baseline hazard function, to match the inherent advantage of the Cox method.
To simulate a simple survival dataset, use the sim.survdata() function with the num.data.frames. argument set to 1.


simdata <- sim.survdata(N=1000, T=100, num.data.frames=1)



Other features can be changed too, including the number of observation (N argument), maximum survival time (T argument), covariates number (xvars argument), and proportion of right censored observations (censor argument).


simdata <- sim.survdata(N=700, T=250, xvars=5, censor=.2, num.data.frames = 1)



To combine existing datasets with simulated duration and censor, used the X argument. Three variables (postel, rgovm and pgovno) from the included martinvanberg dataset were used.


mv.data <- dplyr::select(martinvanberg, postel, rgovm, pgovno)
simdata <- sim.survdata(T=100, X=mv.data, num.data.frames = 1)

head(simdata$data, 6)


  postel rgovm pgovno  y failed
1      1  3.01      2 69   TRUE
2      1  1.95      2 71   TRUE
3      1  2.36      2 95   TRUE
4      0  2.36      2 67  FALSE
5      0  2.36      2 54   TRUE
6      1  1.46      2 67   TRUE
